2 Load data

## read ctg data files
ctg_data <- lapply(list.files("~/tas/data/replicate_1/", full.names = T, 
    pattern = "TAS"), function(f) read_tsv(f, col_names = F, 
    col_types = "cci") %>% `colnames<-`(c("screen", "well", "pcount"))) %>% 
    bind_rows() %>% separate(screen, c("date", "operator", "mithras", 
    "experiment_id"), sep = "_", remove = FALSE) %>% separate(experiment_id, 
    c("experiment", "line", "TAS_concentration")) %>% # join compound annotation data
full_join(., lapply(list.files("~/tas/data/annotations/", full.names = T), 
    function(f) read_csv(f)) %>% bind_rows() %>% rename(well = destination.well) %>% 
    select(drug, well, Source_Position, Source) %>% separate(well, 
    c("row", "col"), sep = 1, remove = FALSE) %>% mutate(drug = if_else(is.na(drug), 
    Source, drug), drug = if_else(well == "J19", "DMSO", drug), 
    combination = if_else(col == "13", FALSE, TRUE)))

3 Inspect screening data

First I want to gain a broad overview of the asssay plates.

tmp <- ctg_data
raw_grid(data = tmp$pcount, well = tmp$well, plate_id = tmp$screen, 
    plate = 384, ncols = 6) + theme_minimal() + scale_fill_viridis() + 
    theme(aspect.ratio = 0.66667)

4 QC

Now I look at the distribution of controls in the first screening replicate.

coi <- c("Stauro_500nM", "DMSO")
ctg_data %>% filter(drug %in% coi) %>% ggplot(aes(drug, pcount, 
    color = combination)) + geom_jitter(alpha = 0.7) + facet_grid(line ~ 
    TAS_concentration) + theme_bw()

The distribution seems to be quiet good. Only plate TAS-27-4 seems to have suffered a bit due to a delayed CTG readout. I now go on calculating the z-factors for each plate for combined and uncombined wells.

ctg_data %>% filter(drug %in% coi) %>% group_by(line, TAS_concentration, 
    drug, combination) %>% summarise(sd = sd(pcount, na.rm = TRUE), 
    mean = mean(pcount, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% group_by(line, TAS_concentration, 
    combination) %>% summarise(zfactor = 1 - ((3 * sum(sd))/abs(range(mean)[1] - 
    range(mean)[2]))) %>% mutate(qc = if_else(zfactor < 0.5, 
    FALSE, TRUE)) %>% ggplot(aes(combination, zfactor, color = qc)) + 
    geom_point(alpha = 0.7, size = 3) + facet_grid(line ~ TAS_concentration) + 
    theme_bw() + geom_hline(yintercept = 0.5)

Also the z-factors are okay for all plates. Three plates have slight losses in assay quality, however, this seems still acceptable. I would continue
